{
  "answer": "In Mirza Ghalib's ghazal, the heart's lament (*naala*)—an inner wail of anguish—is depicted as failing to escape the lips, instead transforming into a permanent physical scar (*daagh*) on the chest (*seena*, evoking the heart). This containment physicalizes the grief as an indelible mark of unexpressed torment, underscoring the lover's futile internalization of pain: \"The cry un-cried becomes a scar upon the soul for me\".[^1]\n\nIqbal's \"Nawa-e-Gham\" (\"Melody of Sorrow\") portrays the heart or life-force as a silent lute (*sitār*), pregnant with mute songs yet dormant in cosmic silence. A celestial sigh from Sinai descends like a plectrum, transforming this stillness into a faint, hopeless melody that rings as a \"marching-bell for caravans of cries.\" The figure evolves from passive vessel to active voice of sorrow, attaining its essence (\"height\") through divine activation.[^2]\n\nGhalib's transformation is tragic stasis: lament objectified as bodily wound, trapped and intensifying isolation. Iqbal's is redemptive awakening: silence alchemized into universal dirge, aligning personal grief with spiritual/cosmic purpose.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/25-dar-khur-e-qahr-o-ghazab-jab-koi-hum-sa-na-hua/translation/#p-607821).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/19-nawa-e-gham/translation/).",
